From the moment you hold your baby in your arms,
you will never be the same.
You might long for the person you were before,
When you had freedom and time,
And nothing in particular to worry about.
You will know tiredness like you never knew it before,
And days will run into days that are exactly the same,
Full of feedings and burping,
Diaper changes and crying,
Whining and fighting,
Naps or a lack of naps,
It might seem like a never-ending cycle. 

But don't forget...
There is a last time for everything.
There will come a time when you will feed your baby
for the very last time.
They will fall asleep on you after a long day
And it will be the last time you ever hold your
sleeping child.
One day you will carry them on your hip,
then set them down,
And never pick them up that way again.
You will scrub their hair in the bath one night
And from that day on they will want to bathe alone.
They will hold your hand to cross the road,
Then never reach for it again.
They will creep into your room at midnight for cuddles,
And it will be the last night you ever wake to this.
One afternoon you will sing the wheels on the bus*
and do all the actions,
Then never sing them that song again.
They will kiss you goodbye at the school gate,
The next day they will ask to walk to the gate alone.
You will read a final bedtime story and wipe your
last dirty face.
They will one day run to you with arms raised,
for the very last time.
The thing is, you won't even know it's the last time
Until there are no more times, and even then,
it will take you a while to realise.
So while you are living in these times,
remember there are only so many of them and
when they are gone,
you will yearn for just one more day of them.

For one last time

A few reasons I run my humidifier in my home day in and day out 🤍

Dry air may cause a wide variety of unpleasant symptoms to your skin. When forced-air heating is running and causes the humidity levels to dip down to between 20-30%, or the weather is particularly dry, your skin starts to lose its moisture. This can lead to your skin feeling tight, dry, itchy and flaky.

Protect Your Throat
When exposed to indoor air that has too little moisture, it’s possible for your vocal chords to become dry and scratchy. If these conditions persist and your throat continues to feel irritated for long durations, it’s possible that you may become hoarse and lose your voice.
This is especially true if you were recently exposed to the flu or a virus. Humidifiers have also been shown to be an effective tool in the fight against croup, a childhood virus that causes inflammation in the upper airways and leads to a barking type of cough and hoarseness.

Halt the Spread of Flu Germs
Using a humidifier can also help you avoid getting the flu in the first place. A study by the National Academy of Sciences found a strong correlation between dry conditions and the transmission and survival of the influenza virus.
Researchers found that when the amount of absolute humidity in the air was too low, the flu virus was able to survive longer and be spread easier amongst everyone. By using a humidifier in your home during flu season, you are more likely to create an environment that is less favorable for influenza to survive, thus decreasing your chances of catching it.

Help Warm Your Home
The moister the air is in your home, the warmer it will feel. On the flip side, drier air tends to feel chillier. Having a humidifier running in the winter will help keep temperatures at a comfortable level, without putting extra strain on your heater. In fact, it’s recommended that you use both of these appliances in tandem when the temperature starts to drop.

Bereaved Mother’s Day honors Mother’s who have lost a child and also recognizes women who cannot be a Mother due to infertility or other health reasons.

The toilet is the best way to release the pelvic floor and help the baby descend into the pelvis. 

Contractions on the toilet can be super intense, but that’s because they are super productive!

Laboring on the toilet also allows you to be in a supported squat. When we squat, our pelvis opens up by 30 percent, which gives our baby extra space to engage with our cervix and keeps our labor progressing smoothly. 

When we sit on the toilet, we naturally let our pelvic floor relax. When we allow these muscles to soften, all of the hard work our uterus is doing pays off by allowing our cervix to thin, dilate, and get us closer to meeting our baby. 

When I believe someone still has progress to be made during labor, but they need time to rest, I put them in this fantastic active rest position.

10CM doesn’t equal time to push..

You can push at 10CM BUT is your body truly ready to push at 10CM is the question? You hear about Moms pushing for hours and hours and I believe this can be because of the rush to get the Mom to start pushing before her body is ready. 10CM doesn’t mean the baby is in the right station or ready to be born. 

So here’s the truth your body is almost always going to push your baby out whether you are voluntarily pushing or not 🤍

Pushing isn’t actually necessary during normal labor and birth. When left undisturbed, a birthing woman can experience what is known as the fetal, or fetus, ejection reflex (FER). 

Let’s talk about Fetal Ejection Reflex and what it is🤍

The reflex, also known as the Ferguson reflex, is when a woman’s body expels her baby without actively pushing. The reflex is involuntary: quite literally, her body is doing the work without any thought.

If we look to nature, we can see the fetus ejection reflex occurs naturally when mammals birth in a place where they feel safe and private, which allows them to birth quickly and easily.

Humans have the same needs for birth as other mammals do.

No matter how you choose to have your baby.. 

Just make sure it’s beautiful. If it’s beautiful for you that’s all that matters.🤍 

Fear, trauma, and negativity. Should not hold a space in your birth story 🤍

If a baby isn’t able to stay asleep or settled without a binky or breast in their mouth this could be a sign they need help with their airway or oral function. Some people see this as a sign that their baby may need sleep training or a binky. Instead this could be a great opportunity to have your babies oral function looked in to🤍 

Truth be told babies have existed for decades before a binky was offered and were able to be soothed.

So the question is what does a healthy airway look like for babies? Their lips will be closed, their tongue will be sealed to the roof of the mouth, and they will have good jaw alignment. When a binky is given the lips open, the tongue is low in the mouth, and instead there’s a firm structure pushing on the roof of the mouth. This can be a problem because unfortunately over time this will permanently will change the structure of the face and airway!

In the beginnings of our children’s life we as parents strive to provide the safest environment for our little ones. However, a lurking threat has found its way into the heart of baby care items.. Microplastics in baby bottles. These microscopic plastics pose concerns for the health and well-being of our infants.

Microplastics, minuscule plastic particles measuring less than 5 millimeters, have invaded many of our everyday items we rely on, including baby bottles.

As parents we have to realize we need to  select baby bottles for their safety, the realization that plastics, known for their durability, are also capable of breaking down into tiny, potentially harmful particles, raises many  alarms. Studies have shown that when plastic bottles are exposed to heat, repeated washing, or wear and tear, they release microplastics, which can then leach into the liquid inside.

The implications of exposing infants to microplastics are not yet fully understood, but emerging research suggests potential risks. These particles can contain harmful chemicals, such as phthalates and bisphenol A (BPA), known for their endocrine-disrupting properties.
